Motivation

  • While it is easy for human brain to instantly associate the handwritten image (left) to the number 4, it is not as straightforward for computers to do so

  • How can we train computers to “read” numbers from images?

Motivation

  • In class (week 8), we learnt character recognition by means of Kernel Density Function. Specifically, we use radial basis function to get empirical density functions and use maximum log likelihood to select character.

  • In this tutorial, let’s take a look at how we can perform image classification (on handwritten numbers using MNIST dataset) through the use of Ensemble learning

Bias-Variance Trade-Off

  • A low bias and a low variance are the two most fundamental features expected when training a model, though they most often vary in opposite directions

  • We want our model to have enough degrees of freedom to resolve the underlying complexity of the (train) data that we are working with, but we also not want too much degrees of freedom to avoid high variance on the (test) data

Weak Learners

  • In ensemble learning, we call weak learners models that are used for designing more complex models by combining several of them

  • Usually, these weak learners perform not so well by themselves either because they have a high bias or because they have too much variance

  • This is where the bias-variance trade-off comes in where we try to find a balance between bias and variance by using ensemble learning

Ensemble Learning

  • The old saying “Unity is Strength” expresses pretty well the underlying idea that rules the very powerful ensemble methods in machine learning

Ensemble Learning

  • Ensemble methods aim at improving predictability in models by combining several weak learners to make one reliable strong learner, thus increasing the accuracy of the model

  • Ensemble methods are ideal for both regression and classification, where they reduce bias and variance to boost the accuracy of models

Ensemble Methods

  • There are mainly two types of ensemble methods, homogeneous and heterogeneous

  • Homogeneous ensemble methods have only a single-type of base learning algorithm (For example, weak learners are only built using decision trees)

  • On the other hand, heterogeneous ensemble consists of members having different base learning algorithms (For example, weak learners are built based on SVM, ANN and decision trees)

  • There are three major kinds of meta-algorithms that aims at combining weak learners (Bagging, Boosting & Stacking):

  • Recall that we have learnt bagging in The Analytics Edge (TAE)

Recall from TAE: Bagging

  • Bagging is a homogeneous ensemble method

  • When using bagging, weak learners are learned independently from each other in parallel

Ensemble Methods

  • This tutorial will be focusing on the boosting method
  • Let us now take a look at the boosting method in more depth

Boosting

  • Just like bagging, boosting is also a homogeneous ensemble method

  • On the other hand, when using boosting, weak learners are learned sequentially in a very adaptive way (a base model depends on the previous ones)

  • In short, boosting seek to improve the prediction power by training a sequence of weak models , each compensating the weaknesses of its predecessors

Boosting

Gradient Boosting

  • Supervised Learning Algorithm

  • Gradient Boosting (Also known as Gradient Boosted Decision Trees) uses an ensemble of decision (classification) trees to predict a target label

Decision Trees (Classification)

  • Recall from The Analytics Edge (TAE):

  • A decision tree is a tree where each node represents a feature, each branch represents a decision and each leaf represents an outcome

  • A decision tree takes a set of input features and splits input data recursively based on those input features

  • This is an iterative process where there is no more branching of tree if some stop condition is met

Decision Trees (Classification)

  • Recall from The Analytics Edge (TAE):

  • To decide on which separation at each node is “best”, we need to measure and compare impurity

Single Tree (Weak Learner)

  • In the context of gradient boosting, the weak learner would be a decision tree

Many Trees (Strong Learner)

  • Many decision trees together will build a strong learner

  • Before diving into the mechanics of Gradient Boosting in classification problem, let us first recap the roles that log(Odds) and log(Likelihood) play in logistic regression

Recap (In logistic Regression)

  • Recall what Odds is:

  • Odds: Simply put, odds are the chances of success divided by the chances of failure.

  • **Note: Odds are not probabilities!

  • For example, You might say that the odds in favour of your team winning the game are 5 to 3:

  • Visually I have 8 games in total, 5 of which my team will win and 3 of which my team will lose, so the odds are 5 to 3, and we can write the Odds as a fraction 5/3 = 1.7

Recap (In logistic Regression)

  • Recall what log(odds) is:

  • Simply the logarithm of odds, carries the same meaning as Odds, but just that log(odds) makes things symmetrical, easier to interpret and hence easier for statistics

  • The log-likelihood value for a given model can range from negative infinity to positive infinity. The actual log-likelihood value for a given model is mostly meaningless, but it’s useful for comparing two or more models

  • The loss function of gradient boosting is then expressed in terms of log(Odds) as shown:

Big Idea of Gradient Boosting

  • This diagram represents the outcome of gradient boosting. We start off with just one leaf associated with an initial prediction. We then build more trees to improve on the previous prediction.

  • The objective of gradient boosting is to minimize the loss function by looking for optimal \(\gamma\) value.

  • \(\gamma\) is a parameter that potentially improves the \(log(odds)\) (and hence the predicted probability) with each iteration.

  • Learning rates are the hyper meters which controls how much we are adjusting the weights of our network with respect to the loss gradient. The learning rate affects how quickly our model can converge to a local minima (our best accuracy). In the diagram above, 0.1 is a learning rate.

  • The relationship is given by: new_weight = existing_weight - learning_rate * gradient

  • We basically update the predictions such that the sum of our residuals is close to zero and the predicted values are close to actual values.

Gradient Boosted Trees - Diabetes Example

  • We will go through step-by-step of how the Gradient Boosting Algorithm is used to predict this Diabetes example. This small example is used to illustrate the big idea. For simplicity, we will only consider binary classification

  • We have 3 predictor variables: “BMI”, “Age”, and “Sex”. We have our outcome: “Is diabetic” which is a categorical data. Hence, we will use classification modeling in our Gradient Boosting Algorithm.

  • We want to predict whether an individual will have a diabetes based on “BMI”, “Age”, and “Sex”.

Gradient Boosted Trees - Diabetes Example

  • As mentioned in the big idea, we first start with a initial prediction. This will be the first leaf. Since this is a classification problem, our initial prediction equals \(log(odd)^{(a)}\). In our case, if 2 people are diabetic and 4 are not diabetic, we get \(log(odd)=log(\frac{2}{4})=-0.69\). Using logistic function to convert this \(log(odd)\) into a probability: (refer to recap slide)

    \[Predicted\ probability\ of\ being\ diabetic = \frac{e^{log(odds)}}{1+e^{log(odds)}}=0.33\]

  • We can then classify that if the \(probability>0.5\), the person is diabetic.

  • Thus, in our initial step, ALL the outcome is not diabetic since the probability is \(0.33 (<0.5)\)

  • Next, we find the residual for every individual in the dataset using observed probability minus predicted probability.

  • (a): To understand why \(log(odds)\) is being used as initial prediction, please refer to slide …

Gradient Boosted Trees - Diabetes Example

  • \(Residual = Observed - Predicted\)

  • Using the 3 predictor variables, next we build a tree to predict the residuals. Things will become clearer as we finish one iteration. Please be patient.

  • Why predict the residuals?

  • Recall: The main idea of boosting is to add new models to the ensemble sequentially. At each particular iteration, a new weak, base-leaner model is trained with respect to the error of the whole ensemble learnt so far.

Gradient Boosted Trees - Diabetes Example

  • From the residual, we can derive such decision tree where there are only 4 leaves. However, in practice, people often set the maximum number of leaves to be between 8 and 32. The residuals are colored coded for easy tracking of where it belongs in the leaves of the tree.

  • Next, let’s us calculate the output values for the leaves.

Gradient Boosted Trees - Diabetes Example

  • We will use the transformation function to calculate the output values of the residual leaf:

\[ \frac{\sum residual_i}{\sum [Previous\ Prob._i *(1-Previous\ Prob._i)]} \]

  • This transformation function is derived by minimizing the loss function by looking for the optimal \(\gamma\) (refer to Big Idea slide for more information).

  • The derivation of this transformation function can be found in Annex slide.

  • Now, we are ready to update our predictions by combining the initial leaf with the new tree.

Gradient Boosted Trees - Diabetes Example

  • To do the update, let’s first calculate the \(log(odd)\ prediction\) for all individuals or observations

  • Let’s consider a female age 36 as an example: \(log(odds)\ Prediction = -0.69+0.1*(-1.49)=-0.84\) where \(0.1\) is the learning rate (refer to Big Idea slide)

  • This is equivalent to \(Probability = \frac{e^{-0.84}}{1+e^{-0.84}}=0.30\)

Gradient Boosted Trees - Diabetes Example

  • Now, we have a completed list of new predicted probability.

Gradient Boosted Trees - Diabetes Example

  • Now, we can compute the new residual based on the new predicted probability.

  • Once we have the residual, the new cycle begins again.
  • We also see that after one iteration, the predicted probability of (Female, 36) is decreased from original prediction of 0.33 to 0.30. Thus, we are taking a small step in the right direction.

Gradient Boosted Trees - Diabetes Example

  • To summarize, we started with just a leaf, which made one prediction for every individual.

  • Then we build a tree based on the residuals. Then we calculated output values for each leave and we scale it with a learning rate. Then we built another tree based on the new residuals. Then we calculated the output values for each leave and we scale it with the same learning rate as well.

  • This process repeats till we have made the maximum number of trees specified, or the residuals get super small.

  • So this is how gradient boosted tree work in our small diabetes example. In the next slide, we will take a look at how gradient boosting is similar to gradient descent idea.

Link: Gradient Descent

  • In Gradient descent, it can be succinctly written as: \(p_{n+1}=p_n-\eta\nabla f(p_n)\) where \(\eta\) is the learning rate

  • Gradient Descent Algorithm iteratively calculates the next point using gradient at the current position, then scales it (by a learning rate) and subtracts obtained value from the current position (makes a step). It subtracts the value because we want to minimise the function (to maximise it would be adding) (Robert Kwiatkowski, 2021)

  • In Gradient Boosting, we are finding a \(\gamma\) value that minimizes the loss function. In the diagram below, we want to find the position of the purple ball that gives the smallest loss function value.

  • Now, let’s move on to the scary part: Mathematics behind Gradient Boosted Trees.

Gradient Boosted Trees - Math Explained

  • Input: Data \({(x_i,y_i)^n_{i=1}}\) , and a differentiable Loss Function \(L(y_i,F(x))\)

  • Step 1: Initialize model with a constant value: \(F_0(x) =\displaystyle argmin_{\gamma} \sum_{i=1}^{n} L(y_i,\gamma)\)

  • Step 2: for m =1 to M:

      1. Compute \(r_{im}=-[\frac{\partial L(y_i, F(x_i)}{\partial F(x_i)}]_{F(x)=F_{m-1}(x)}\) for \(i=1,...,n\)
      1. Fit a regression tree to the \(r_{im}\) values and creates terminal regions \(R_{im},\) for \(j=1,...,J_m\)
      1. For \(j=1...J_m\) compute \(\gamma_{jm}=\displaystyle argmin_{\gamma} \sum_{x_i\in R_{ij}} L(y_i,F_{m-1}(x_i)+\gamma)\)
      1. Update \(F_m(x)=F_{m-1}(x)+v \sum_{j=1}^{J_m} \gamma_mI(x\in R_{jm})\)

  • Step 3: Output \(F_M(x)\)

Gradient Boosted Trees - Input

  • Input: Data \({(x_i,y_i)^n_{i=1}}\) , and a differentiable Loss Function \(L(y_i,F(x))\)

    ……………………………………………………………………………………………………………………………………..

  • \({(x_i,y_i)^n_{i=1}}\) represents data points where \(x_i\) is the row of features and \(y_i\) is the label or observed value.

  • \(L(y_i,F(x))=-y_i *log(odds)+log(1+e^{log(odds)})\) represents the loss function between our observed value \(y_i\)and the predicted value \(F(x)\) or \(log(odds)\).

  • The loss function value is high when the label and prediction do not agree, and the loss function value is zero when they are in perfect agreement.

Gradient Boosted Trees - Step 1

  • Input: Data \({(x_i,y_i)^n_{i=1}}\) , and a differentiable Loss Function \(L(y_i,F(x))\)

  • Step 1: Initialize model with a constant value: \(F_0(x) =\displaystyle argmin_{\gamma} \sum_{i=1}^{n} L(y_i,\gamma)\)

    ……………………………………………………………………………………………………………………………………..

  • This step is to find a optimal value of \(\gamma\) that minimizes the loss function \(L(y_i,\gamma)\) where observed value \(y_i\) and predicted value \(\gamma\) or \(log(odds)\)

  • Since \(L(y_i,F(x))=-y_i *log(odds)+log(1+e^{log(odds)})\), we have: \(\frac{\partial L}{\partial F(x)}=-y_i+\frac{e^{log(odds)}}{1+e^{log(odds)}}=-y_i+p\)

  • Equate \(\frac{\partial L}{\partial F(x)}\) to \(0\), we get \(F_0(x) =log(odds)=log(\frac{p}{1-p})\). Note: This is our initial prediction which corresponds to \(log(\frac{2}{4})\) in the diabetes example.

Gradient Boosted Trees - Step 2 - (A)

  • Step 2: for m =1 to M:

      1. Compute \(r_{im}=-[\frac{\partial L(y_i, F(x_i)}{\partial F(x_i)}]_{F(x)=F_{m-1}(x)}\) for \(i=1,...,n\)

    ……………………………………………………………………………………………………………………………………..

  • In this step, we are essentially calculating the Residuals (also seen in the Diabetes example previously)

  • \(-[\frac{\partial L(y_i, F(x_i)}{\partial F(x_i)}]\) is the derivative of the loss function with respect to \(F(x_i)\) or \(log(odds)\).

    \[-[\frac{\partial L(y_i, F(x_i)}{\partial F(x_i)}]=y_i-\frac{e^{log(odds)}}{1+e^{log(odds)}}=y_i-p\\=observed-predicted\\=residual\]

  • \({F(x)=F_{m-1}(x)}\) means that we will plug in the most recent predicted \(log(odds)\)

  • Thus, \(r_{im}\) is the residual for each sample in the dataset for the first tree.

Gradient Boosted Trees - Step 2 - (B)

  • Step 2: for m =1 to M:

      1. Compute \(r_{im}=-[\frac{\partial L(y_i, F(x_i)}{\partial F(x_i)}]_{F(x)=F_{m-1}(x)}\) for \(i=1,...,n\)
      1. Fit a regression tree to the \(r_{im}\) values and creates terminal regions \(R_{im},\) for \(j=1,...,J_m\)

    ……………………………………………………………………………………………………………………………………..

  • In this step, we build the regression tree fit to the residuals and create terminal regions \(R_{jm}\) or output values (seen in diabetes example) for all the leaves in the tree

Gradient Boosted Trees - Step 2 - (C)

  • Step 2: for m =1 to M:

      1. Compute \(r_{im}=-[\frac{\partial L(y_i, F(x_i)}{\partial F(x_i)}]_{F(x)=F_{m-1}(x)}\) for \(i=1,...,n\)
      1. Fit a regression tree to the \(r_{im}\) values and creates terminal regions \(R_{im},\) for \(j=1,...,J_m\)
      1. For \(j=1...J_m\) compute \(\gamma_{jm}=\displaystyle argmin_{\gamma} \sum_{x_i\in R_{ij}} L(y_i,F_{m-1}(x_i)+\gamma)\)

    ……………………………………………………………………………………………………………………………………..

  • For \(j=1...J_m\) means that for each leaf in the new tree we compute an output value \(\gamma_{jm}\) , where m is our tree

  • \(\gamma_{jm}=\displaystyle argmin_{\gamma} \sum_{x_i\in R_{ij}} L(y_i,F_{m-1}(x_i)+\gamma)\) means that we are trying to find the value of \(\gamma\) that, when added to the most recent predicted \(log(odds)\), minimized the Loss Function

  • Derivation of \(\gamma_{jm}\) can be referred to in Annex (Just for your knowledge)

Gradient Boosted Trees - Step 2 - (D) and Step 3

  • Step 2: for m =1 to M:

      1. Compute \(r_{im}=-[\frac{\partial L(y_i, F(x_i)}{\partial F(x_i)}]_{F(x)=F_{m-1}(x)}\) for \(i=1,...,n\)
      1. Fit a regression tree to the \(r_{im}\) values and creates terminal regions \(R_{im},\) for \(j=1,...,J_m\)
      1. For \(j=1...J_m\) compute \(\gamma_{jm}=\displaystyle argmin_{\gamma} \sum_{x_i\in R_{ij}} L(y_i,F_{m-1}(x_i)+\gamma)\)
      1. Update \(F_m(x)=F_{m-1}(x)+v \sum_{j=1}^{J_m} \gamma_mI(x\in R_{jm})\)

  • Step 3: Output \(F_M(x)\)

    ……………………………………………………………………………………………………………………………………..

  • In this step, we make a new prediction for each sample based on our output value \(\gamma_{jm}\) we calculated from the previous step.

  • \(F_m(x)=F_{m-1}(x)+v \sum_{j=1}^{J_m} \gamma_mI(x\in R_{jm})\) represents a new prediction based on the old prediction \(F_{m-1}(x)+ learning\ rate\ v\) and all the output values \(\gamma_{jm}\) of all the leaves

  • This completes the first iteration and we continue to repeat step 2 (A)-(D) for M number of trees to output the latest prediction \(F_m(x)\)

Extreme Gradient Boosting

  • Now that we have understood how Gradient Boosting works, Extreme Gradient Boosting is just Gradient Boosting, but with the addition of L1 and/or L2 regularizers.

  • Regularization techniques are used to reduce overfitting effects by adding penalty terms in the loss function. For more information on how regularization works, please refer to the lecture on “Model Selection Techniques” in week 5 (slides 48-52).

  • In order to shorten the training time of the model, we will instead use XGBoost which is 10 times faster than Gradient Boosted Tree while the underlying principal is still based on Gradient Boosted Tree.

Code implementation - Dataset Background

  • Let’s now try to apply what we learnt into MNIST dataset to predict the handwritten digit.

  • MNIST dataset is a large database of handwritten digits that is commonly used fro training various image processing systems. It contains 60,000 training images and 10,000 testing images.

  • The set of images in the MNIST database was created in 1998 as a combination of two of NIST’s databases: Special Database 1 and Special Database 3. Special Database 1 and Special Database 3 consist of digits written by high school students and employees of the United States Census Bureau, respectively.

  • Next, we will go through step-by-step on the implementation.

Code Implementation - Steps

  1. Import dataset

  2. Split & Transform the dataset

  3. Train the model

  4. Fine-tune the model

  5. Predict the model

Code Implementation - Import Dataset

install.packages("devtools")
devtools::install_github("jlmelville/mnist")
library(mnist)
# fetch the data set from the MNIST website
mnist <- download_mnist()
# view the fifth digit
show_digit(mnist, 21)

Code Implementation - Split & Transform the dataset

# first 60,000 instances are the training set
mnist_train <- head(mnist, 60000)
# the remaining 10,000 are the test set
mnist_test <- tail(mnist, 10000)
# Split training and testing set each for features and label
set.seed(1)
label <- mnist_train$Label
numfeatures <- ncol(mnist)
train.data <- as.matrix(mnist_train[,1:numfeatures-1])
train.label <- as.matrix(mnist_train[,numfeatures])
test.data <- as.matrix(mnist_test[,1:numfeatures-1])
test.label <- as.matrix(mnist_test[,numfeatures])
#Next, we transform the training and testing data sets into xgb.DMatrix objects that are used for fitting the XGBoost model and predicting new outcomes. 
# Transform the two data sets into xgb.Matrix
xgb.train = xgb.DMatrix(data=train.data,label=train.label)
xgb.test = xgb.DMatrix(data=test.data,label=test.label)

Code Implementation - Train the model

set.seed(123)
num_class = length(levels(label))
params = list(
  booster="gbtree",
  objective="multi:softprob",
  eval_metric="mlogloss",
  num_class=num_class
)
set.seed(123)
xgb.fit=xgb.train(
  params=params,
  data=xgb.train,
  nrounds=5,
  nthreads=2,
  early_stopping_rounds=10,
  watchlist=list(train=xgb.train,test=xgb.test),
  verbose=1
)
xgb.pred = predict(xgb.fit,test.data,reshape=T)
xgb.pred = as.data.frame(xgb.pred)
colnames(xgb.pred) = levels(label)
xgb.pred$prediction = apply(xgb.pred,1,function(x) colnames(xgb.pred)[which.max(x)])
xgb.pred$label = test.label
result = (sum(xgb.pred$prediction==xgb.pred$label)/nrow(xgb.pred))*100
print(paste("The accuracy of this model is", result, "%","."))

Code Implementation - Train the model

Code Implementation - Fine-tune the model

  • To fine-tune the training model, we changed the “eta” (learning rate) from the default 0.3 to 0.1 and increase “nrounds” (number of iterations) to 300 so that we can maximize the model in terms of accuracy. At the same time, we set L1 regularizer (alpha) and L2 regularizer (lambda) to prevent overfitting of the trees.

  • Also, we increase the “max_depth” from the default 6 to 10 to build deeper trees.

set.seed(123)
num_class = length(levels(label))
params = list(
  booster="gbtree",
  eta=0.1,
  max_depth=10,
  lambda=0.1,
  alpha=0.1,
  subsample=0.75,
  colsample_bytree=0.5,
  objective="multi:softprob",
  eval_metric="mlogloss",
  num_class=num_class
)
set.seed(123)
xgb.fit=xgb.train(
  params=params,
  data=xgb.train,
  nrounds=300,
  nthreads=2,
  early_stopping_rounds=10,
  watchlist=list(train=xgb.train,test=xgb.test),
  verbose=1
)

Code Implementation - Predict the model

xgb.pred = predict(xgb.fit,test.data,reshape=T)
xgb.pred = as.data.frame(xgb.pred)
colnames(xgb.pred) = levels(label)
xgb.pred$prediction = apply(xgb.pred,1,function(x) colnames(xgb.pred)[which.max(x)])
xgb.pred$label = test.label
result = (sum(xgb.pred$prediction==xgb.pred$label)/nrow(xgb.pred))*100
print(paste("The accuracy of this model is", result, "%","."))

Annex

  • For simplicity, we will derive the output value \(\gamma_{j,m}\)

\[ {\gamma_{2,1}=\ argmin_{\gamma} \sum_{x_i\in R_{ij}} L(y_i,F_{m-1}(x_i)+\gamma)}\\ = L(y_2,F_{m-1}(x_2)+\gamma) +L(y_3,F_{m-2}(x_3)+\gamma)\\ We\ can\ approximate\ the\ loss\ function\ with\ second\ order\ Taylor\ Polynomials\ and\ we\ get:\\L(y_2,F_{m-1}(x_2)+\gamma) +L(y_3,F_{m-2}(x_3)+\gamma)\\\approx L(y_2,F_{m-1}(x_2)) +L(y_3,F_{m-1}(x_3))\\+[\frac{d(y_2,F_{m-1}(x_2))}{dF()} +\frac{d(y_3,F_{m-1}(x_3))}{dF()}]\gamma\\+\frac{1}{2}[\frac{d^2(y_3,F_{m-1}(x_3))}{dF()^2} +\frac{d^2(y_3,F_{m-1}(x_3))}{dF()^2}]\gamma^2 \]

\[ \frac{d(L(y_2,F_{m-1}(x_2)+\gamma) +L(y_3,F_{m-2}(x_3)+\gamma))}{d\gamma}\\\approx [\frac{d(y_2,F_{m-1}(x_2))}{dF()} +\frac{d(y_3,F_{m-1}(x_3))}{dF()}]\gamma\\+[\frac{d^2(y_3,F_{m-1}(x_3))}{dF()^2} +\frac{d^2(y_3,F_{m-1}(x_3))}{dF()^2}]\gamma^2 = 0 \]

\[ \\solving\ for\ \gamma, we \ get:\\\gamma=\frac{-[\frac{d(y_2,F_{m-1}(x_2))}{dF()} +\frac{d(y_3,F_{m-1}(x_3))}{dF()}]}{[\frac{d^2(y_3,F_{m-1}(x_3))}{dF()^2} +\frac{d^2(y_3,F_{m-1}(x_3))}{dF()^2}]} \\=\frac{y_2 - \frac{e^{log(odds)}}{1+e^{log(odds)}}+y_3 - \frac{e^{log(odds)}}{1+e^{log(odds)}}}{p_2*(1-p_2)+p_3*(1-p_3)}\\=\frac{(y_2-p_2)+(y_3-p_3)}{p_2*(1-p_2)+p_3*(1-p_3)}\\=\frac{Residual_2+Residual_3}{p_2*(1-p_2)+p_3*(1-p_3)} \]
